{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480197"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:38:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:38:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"24"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/24"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.04,0.11,0.69,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"24"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113486"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/24"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"24"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95503"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30334"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41958"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46951"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113486"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after waking from sleep acutely short of breath and subsequently calling an ambulance. In the preceding two months, he has noticed worsening shortness of breath on exertion and usually sleeps propped up on two to three pillows at night. He has a history of long-standing, poorly controlled type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension. His regular medication is metformin, but he admits to poor compliance. He does not regularly visit a General Practitioner.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 160/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has an S3 gallop, bilateral basal crackles, and pitting oedema up to the ankles. Urinalysis is positive for glucose and protein +++. His ECG on presentation is shown (Image) and his chest X-ray shows a cardiothoracic ratio \u0026gt;50% with upper lobe blood diversion. He is started on intravenous furosemide therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management to initiate next?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amiodarone","Atorvastatin","Digoxin","Perindopril","Verapamil"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs consistent with acute decompensated heart failure. The history of orthopnoea, worsening exertional dyspnoea, S3 gallop, and peripheral oedema, along with risk factors of poorly controlled diabetes and hypertension, support this diagnosis. The chest X-ray findings are consistent with heart failure. The ECG shows left ventricular hypertrophy according to the Sokolow-Lyon criteria, likely secondary to hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrent guidelines recommend that all four classes of disease-modifying therapy\u2014renin-angiotensin system inhibitors (RASi), heart failure\u2013specific beta-blockers, mineralocorticoid receptor antagonists (MRA), and sodium-glucose cotransporter two inhibitors (SGLT2i)\u2014should be started at or soon after diagnosis of HFrEF, ideally within two to four weeks, unless contraindicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerindopril\u003C/strong\u003E is an angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor (ACEi) and is representative of the class of renin-angiotensin system inhibitors (RASi), which also includes angiotensin receptor blockers and angiotensin receptor-neprilysin inhibitors. These agents reduce mortality and hospitalisation and also provide blood pressure control. While angiotensin receptor-neprilysin inhibitors have shown superior outcomes to ACEi in some studies, they are not currently funded for first-line use in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtorvastatin\u003C/strong\u003E is a statin used for lipid lowering and cardiovascular risk reduction, particularly in people with ischaemic heart disease. However, statins do not directly improve heart failure outcomes and are not first-line for heart failure management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVerapamil\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker with negative inotropic effects, which can worsen HFrEF. It is contraindicated in this setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigoxin\u003C/strong\u003E may be used in HFrEF with persistent symptoms despite optimal medical therapy. However, it does not reduce mortality and is not first-line for heart failure without arrhythmia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiarrhythmic agent used for rhythm control in atrial fibrillation or ventricular arrhythmias. There is no evidence of arrhythmia in this scenario, so it is not indicated for this patient\u2019s HFrEF management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Initiation of all four classes of disease-modifying therapy is recommended within two to four weeks of diagnosis of heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF), unless contraindicated.","Renin-angiotensin system inhibitors (RASi) are a key first-line therapy in HFrEF.","Calcium channel blockers with negative inotropic effects are contraindicated in heart failure with reduced ejection fraction."],"references":["Taylor CJ, Hobbs FD. Heart failure therapy in patients with coronary artery disease. Curr Opin Pharmacol. 2013;13(2):205-9.","Group NCHFGW, Atherton JJ, Sindone A, De Pasquale CG, Driscoll A, MacDonald PS, et al. National Heart Foundation of Australia and Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Guidelines for the Prevention, Detection, and Management of Heart Failure in Australia 2018. Heart Lung Circ. 2018;27(10):1123-208.","Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF). In: Therapeutic Guidelines: Cardiovascular [Internet]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2023 [cited 2025 Jun 3]. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95503"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"24"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17469"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17469"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bfd2dac7-e1c8-4e19-84a7-a0748f6c882f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bfd2dac7-e1c8-4e19-84a7-a0748f6c882f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":355}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95503"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-12T12:19:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-12T12:20:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"24"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113486"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"